00:09:05.996 --> 00:09:14.348
Concorde boasts something called a "droop snoot", or "droop nose" design.

00:09:14.348 --> 00:09:18.378
If you think this nose, this front of the airplane, looks

00:09:18.378 --> 00:09:22.628
a bit odd, a bit strange, well, you probably aren’t alone.

00:09:23.568 --> 00:09:29.418
When it's lowered, it looks almost like a broken bird’s beak — not quite the

00:09:29.588 --> 00:09:34.408
smooth, rounded nose that you might think of when you imagine an aeroplane.

00:09:35.110 --> 00:09:41.521
However, the "droop snoot" was actually quite necessary to flying the Concorde.

00:09:42.421 --> 00:09:48.861
Because of its unique design, the Concorde flew at a steep angle during takeoff and

00:09:48.861 --> 00:09:55.821
landing, and so the pilot would adjust the plane’s nose so that it was tilting downward.

00:09:57.391 --> 00:10:02.563
