00:10:20.873 --> 00:10:25.173
as opposed to the rectangular wing shape of a typical aeroplane.

00:10:26.093 --> 00:10:32.053
It also had a narrower body than that of a typical aeroplane, it was much thinner.

00:10:33.053 --> 00:10:40.193
Both of these helped the Concorde lift off the ground during takeoff, and minimised the amount

00:10:40.193 --> 00:10:46.843
of drag — or the force that makes it harder for an aeroplane or other object to travel forward.

00:10:47.923 --> 00:10:52.593
Of course, the Concorde boasted incredibly powerful turbojet engines,

00:10:52.833 --> 00:10:59.493
and this combination of slim design and absurd amounts of power allowed

00:10:59.493 --> 00:11:06.643
it to sustain its incredible speed of Mach 2 — almost 2,500 km an hour.

00:11:07.993 --> 00:11:15.795
The Concorde also flew so high that passengers could look out the window and see the earth’s curve.

00:11:16.733 --> 00:11:23.418
It flew this high because the higher you go up, the lower the air pressure becomes, so there

00:11:23.623 --> 00:11:30.583
would be less drag, less resistance, and the plane could go faster while using less fuel.

00:11:31.603 --> 00:11:36.323
